{
  "texts": [
    "Rather than seeking to identify a distinctively cognitive feature shared by internal or external processes, it aims to show that a certain kind of action (i.e., offloading) both plays a cognitive role the agent's wider activities and itself depends on her body and environment in the way envisioned by HEC.",
    "If offloading is a pervasive and transformative feature of human cognition, then both many token instances and possibly many core types of cognitive process will depend on acts of offloading like these.",
    "And if offloading is constituted as such by the external resources it recruits, then HEC will be established (cf.",
    "To get the argument into view, let's start with a non-technical outline (the action theoretic apparatus will come to the fore in § §4-5).",
    "Notice first that an emphasis on offloading onto, or 'coupling' with, external resources puts intentional action at the heart of HEC."
  ]
